<div id="review_3694701416" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3694701416" />
    <a title="W.D. Clarke" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13122795-w-d-clarke"><img alt="W.D. Clarke" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1535550502p2/13122795.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3694701416?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="W.D. Clarke" class="user" itemprop="url" name="W.D. Clarke" href="/user/show/13122795-w-d-clarke">W.D. Clarke</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13122795-w-d-clarke?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3694701416" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17190460916656689859">A perfectly fine first novel in the Graham Greene mode, if a somewhat unthrilling thriller. We get introduced to the world of George Smiley, are treated to a tiny bit of his obsession with highbrow German lit, get plenty of useful backstory, and watch him deploy some tradecraft as he solves the murder of a foreign office subordinate—all very competently executed. I&apos;m no aficionado of the genre (in fact have not read a thriller since bingeing-out on Alistair MacLean wayback in high school!), and </span>
  <span id="freeText17190460916656689859" style="display:none">A perfectly fine first novel in the Graham Greene mode, if a somewhat unthrilling thriller. We get introduced to the world of George Smiley, are treated to a tiny bit of his obsession with highbrow German lit, get plenty of useful backstory, and watch him deploy some tradecraft as he solves the murder of a foreign office subordinate—all very competently executed. I'm no aficionado of the genre (in fact have not read a thriller since bingeing-out on Alistair MacLean wayback in high school!), and am not going to second-guess all the fuss over JLC based on this, his first innings, but I liked it and will proceed with further enquiries.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17190460916656689859" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

